<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-059-049 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 303 165</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  Sept 16 1991 n338 p86(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Taking IT from the top. (senior management embraces InformationTechnology to increase profits and sales) (Services) (part of aspecial section on the biggest and best users of informationtechnology) (Cover Story)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Violino, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The services industry, suffering from the sluggish economy, islooking to information technology (IT) to boost profits orminimize losses.andP;  This industry previously displayed the lowestspending on IT of any industrial sector, but IT is now becoming ahigh priority with top management.andP;  Reader's Digest is making amajor investment in IT over the next five years to improve serviceand deal with rising production costs.andP;  Humana Inc, a health careprovider, is investing in IT to manage its business and handle itsgrowth.andP;  Waste Management Inc of Hinsdale, IL, is usinginformation systems (IS) to track 4 million customers.andP;  GenuineParts Co of Atlanta, GA, is experimenting with paperlesswarehousing; customers use bar-code devices to order auto parts.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Service IndustryInformation resources managementInformation servicesBar codes.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Top 29 service industry companies. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>